{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477136"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:57:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:57:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14180"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14180"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.22,0.07,0.63]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6863"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108255"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6863"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14180"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90656"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"156"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1533"},{"type":"tags","id":"2137"},{"type":"tags","id":"2380"},{"type":"tags","id":"2996"},{"type":"tags","id":"2997"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40445"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40446"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108255"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of headache, confusion, and vomiting. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears lethargic but not dehydrated. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals neck stiffness and photophobia. There are no focal neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum sodium: 124 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum osmolality: 260 mOsm/kg (275-295)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine osmolality: 600 mOsm/kg (50-1200)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine sodium: 80 mmol/L (40-220)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adrenal insufficiency","Psychogenic polydipsia","Cerebral salt wasting syndrome","Diabetes insipidus","Syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a 10-year-old boy with symptoms suggestive of meningitis (headache, confusion, vomiting, fever, neck stiffness, and photophobia) along with laboratory findings consistent with hyponatraemia. The most likely diagnosis in this scenario is \u003Cstrong\u003ESyndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESIADH is characterised by hyponatraemia (serum sodium \u003C135 mmol/L), inappropriately concentrated urine (urine osmolality \u003E100 mOsm/kg), and euvolaemia. In this case, the patient has hyponatraemia (124 mmol/L), concentrated urine (600 mOsm/kg), and appears clinically euvolaemic. The serum osmolality is low (260 mOsm/kg), while the urine sodium is inappropriately normal (80 mmol/L). In the setting of hyponatraemia and low serum osmolality, the kidneys should physiologically attempt to conserve sodium by reducing urinary sodium excretion to very low levels (\u003C20 mmol/L). The presence of normal urine sodium despite hyponatraemia further supports the diagnosis of SIADH. Central nervous system infections, such as meningitis, are common causes of SIADH in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetes insipidus\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by polyuria and polydipsia due to a lack of antidiuretic hormone (ADH) or renal insensitivity to ADH. It typically presents with hypernatraemia and dilute urine, which is not consistent with this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECerebral salt wasting syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in patients with intracranial disorders and is characterised by hyponatraemia and dehydration. While it can be difficult to distinguish from SIADH, this patient appears euvolaemic rather than dehydrated, making SIADH more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsychogenic polydipsia\u003C/strong\u003E involves excessive water intake, leading to hyponatraemia. However, it typically presents with dilute urine and a longer history, which is not consistent with this acute presentation and concentrated urine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hyponatraemia, but it is usually accompanied by hyperkalaemia, hypotension, and other signs of cortisol deficiency, which are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this patient would involve treating the underlying cause (likely meningitis) and addressing the SIADH through fluid restriction. Close monitoring of serum sodium levels is crucial to prevent rapid correction, which can lead to osmotic demyelination syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["SIADH is characterised by hyponatraemia, inappropriately concentrated urine, and euvolaemia.","Common causes of SIADH in children include CNS infections, brain tumours, and certain medications.","In hyponatraemia, the kidneys should normally conserve sodium by reducing urinary sodium excretion."],"references":["Yasir M, Mechanic OJ. Syndrome of Inappropriate Antidiuretic Hormone Secretion. In: StatPearls [Online]. [Updated 2023 Mar 6]. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK507777/","Zheng F, Ye X, Shi X, Lin Z, Yang Z, Jiang L. Hyponatremia in Children With Bacterial Meningitis. Front Neurol. 2019 Apr 30;10:421. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6503034/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90656"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14180"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90656","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90656"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-08T20:00:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-08T20:00:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6863"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108255"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGr